name: Denny Heck
tweet: The bottom line: this bill is a responsible solution that will reduce drug prices for thousands of Washingtonians, improve Medicare coverage, and make smart investments to improve the health of all Americans. I'm proud we passed  #HR3 out of the House today. (14/14)

name: Denny Heck
tweet: Lastly, the bill uses these savings to invest in biomedical research to find cures for the most devastating diseases. And it makes investments to respond to some of our most urgent health issues: health worker shortage, maternal mortality crisis, and opioid epidemic. #HR3 (13/14)  https://t.co/l8YsFFxv7x

name: Denny Heck
tweet: The savings from lower Medicare drug spending are so large that #HR3 also expands Medicare to cover dental, vision and hearing care for all beneficiaries. These are critical elements of total health care, and including them in Medicare is a great achievement. (12/14)  https://t.co/bj73IXNcuF

name: Denny Heck
tweet: For Medicare, the savings are plowed back into improved benefits for seniors. For Medicare beneficiaries, the bill creates a limit on out-of-pocket spending and adds new subsidies for low-income seniors. #HR3 (11/14)  https://t.co/Fg4e8Ai1xb

name: Denny Heck
tweet: These lower prices will be available to both Medicare beneficiaries and individuals with private insurance. This will translate into lower premiums and lower cost sharing for people with private insurance. #HR3 (10/14)

name: Denny Heck
tweet: The bill also imposes financial penalties on drug companies that dramatically hike their prices. To give context, the average annual cost of prescription drugs rose nearly 58% between 2012 and 2017. That number should concern all of us. #HR3 (9/14)

name: Denny Heck
tweet: Now onto the details:   This bill requires HHS to negotiate prices for 50-250 drugs per year (drugmakers will face stiff financial penalties if they refuse to negotiate). Budget experts say the lower prices will reduce fed spending by $456 billion over the 2020s. #HR3 (8/14)

name: Denny Heck
tweet: For years, my colleagues—including my friend, the late Elijah Cummings—worked to make drug price negotiation a reality. Many of these ideas inspired the bill we passed today, #HR3, which is why it is formally named the Elijah E. Cummings Lower Drug Costs Now Act (7/14)

name: Denny Heck
tweet: Medicare, which provides health coverage to 60 million Americans, lacks the power to negotiate drug prices. Almost $1 of every $5 spent in Medicare now goes to prescription drugs, and the total cost over the next decade will be in the trillions of dollars. #HR3 (6/14)

name: Denny Heck
tweet: Parts of our government already negotiate drug prices. The VA is allowed to negotiate prices for the drugs it buys for veterans, and drug companies are required to provide price discounts to Medicaid. As a result, the VA and Medicaid pay much lower drug prices. #HR3 (5/14)

name: Denny Heck
tweet: These problems don’t happen in other countries. The reason prescription drugs are cheaper abroad than in the U.S. is because those governments take a more active role in negotiating lower prices. #HR3 (4/14)  https://t.co/YwlOZdxMLv

name: Denny Heck
tweet: I also hear from constituents who work in the health care industry and see firsthand the impacts of our broken prescription drug market. I received this letter last month from Gordon from Tumwater, and found it particularly moving #HR3 (3/14)  https://t.co/uRINbmC3h2

name: Denny Heck
tweet: I constantly hear from Washingtonians who are outraged about drug prices in America. I’m especially affected by those reliant on a medicine whose price suddenly skyrockets and constituents who ration medications or forego treatment altogether because of costs. #HR3 (2/14)  https://t.co/aBvzDeYzhI

name: Denny Heck
tweet: Today is a historic day in the House. We passed #HR3, a bill that drives down prescription drug costs and uses $500B in Medicare savings to expand benefits for seniors.  Before I get into the details of the bill, let me explain what these reforms mean to me: (1/14)  https://t.co/nVm60PXoEF

name: Denny Heck
tweet: When it comes to climate change, we can’t afford to play catch-up.  My bill would ensure our intelligence agencies exchange and share climate data, equipping these agencies with the tools needed to study and prepare for the climate challenges to come.

name: Denny Heck
tweet: Currently, there’s no centralized office for climate-related issues within our intelligence community. As members of the intelligence community have testified, this has left responsibility for analyzing the effects of climate change splintered across various groups and agencies.

name: Denny Heck
tweet: The intelligence community has stated loudly and clearly that climate hazards pose a real danger to stability and security across the globe: Mass migration. Food and water shortages. Strains on delicate relations around the world.   Climate change is here and we need to be ready.
